GLP-1s might extend human lifespan =E2=80=94 imagine if everyone ate, drank=
, and smoked less. Currently, however, there is no drug on the market =E2=
=80=94 GLP-1 or not =E2=80=94 that has the stated goal of lifespan extensio=
n. That may change soon, but not for the patients you=E2=80=99d imagine.
Loyal [ https://substack.com/redirect/3bfcffa3-9104-46c9-bf6c-a73b388b4fb6?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], a cli=
nical-stage veterinary medicine company, earned what it believes to be the =
first-ever FDA acceptance that a drug can be developed and approved for lif=
espan extension. Its target patient? Large-breed dogs. Loyal is part of a l=
arger firm, Cellular Longevity, that=E2=80=99s developing the first drugs e=
xplicitly intended to extend healthspan and lifespan=E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s =
starting with dogs, but ultimately plans to do so for humans, too.
The company currently has three products in the pipeline, each targeting di=
fferent types of dogs and each at varying stages of the FDA approval proces=
s. And while extending dogs=E2=80=99 lifespan is a win in-and-of-itself (I=
=E2=80=99d literally drain my bank account to extend my large-breed-dog Kin=
g=E2=80=99s life), the hope is that the company=E2=80=99s research and regu=
latory learnings will ultimately help it introduce an anti-aging drug for h=
umans.=20
(3) Scaling deep learning for materials discovery [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/b1bd5256-8656-4d73-b4bf-bc722c7bcba0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Nature
Here we show that graph networks trained at scale can reach unprecedented l=
evels of generalization, improving the efficiency of materials discovery by=
 an order of magnitude. Building on 48,000 stable crystals identified in co=
ntinuing studies improved efficiency enables the discovery of 2.2 million s=
tructures below the current convex hull, many of which escaped previous hum=
an chemical intuition.
DeepMind is on a roll. AlphaGo, AlphaFold, weather predictions, and now mat=
erials.=20
New research from Google=E2=80=99s DeepMind shows that its AI models can si=
mulate millions of novel, possible materials =E2=80=94 far surpassing even =
the most prolific human-staffed chemistry labs. It=E2=80=99s hard to predic=
t all of the ways in which an explosion of material science output would im=
prove our lives =E2=80=94 but just imagine if it was way more affordable to=
 create all of the physical things in the world and that those things were =
essentially perfectly designed for whatever use-case they needed to execute=
=2E Think high-performance batteries, b=
ioactive materials for implants, self-=
healing composites used to make longer lasting rockets, health monitoring t=
extiles, etc etc. Each of these things rely on new material discovery, whic=
h thanks to DeepMind, could now be as simple as running a model.=20
Andrew C=C3=B4t=C3=A9 pointed out [ https://substack.com/redirect/ca881b1d-=
8f4d-45f7-ba86-ea14eabcf0f8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that combined with another just-released paper, An au=
tonomous laboratory for accelerated synthesis of novel materials, making th=
ings in the physical world is about to get really interesting. =20
(4) A first-of-its-kind geothermal project is now operational [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/b45747f4-3216-4ef9-a06d-b3db9cd61154?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Two years ago [ https://substack.com/redirect/ff686039-5364-452d-9c0b-2bc85=
b3e32c4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
], we partnered with clean-energy startup Fervo on the world=E2=80=99s firs=
t corporate agreement to develop an enhanced geothermal power project. Toda=
y, we are pleased to announce that our geothermal project is now operationa=
l and carbon-free electricity has started flowing onto the local grid that =
serves our data centers in Nevada.
Oh look, Google again!
The company announced that its partnership with Fervo to develop enhanced g=
eothermal power is now live, operational, and powering data centers. Doing =
things like simulating millions of novel materials is compute and energy in=
tensive, and the company is making a bunch of bets on how to cleanly power =
its data centers. One of those bets is geothermal.
Geothermal power taps into the Earth's internal heat, typically from areas =
with volcanic activity. Water or other fluids are heated by the Earth=E2=80=
=99s natural heat and brought to the surface, where the steam is used to dr=
ive turbines that generate electricity. That carbon-free electricity can th=
en be used to power data centers.
Historically, geothermal hasn=E2=80=99t been scaled because of geographical=
 limitations, cost disadvantages, and generally a limited knowledge on how =
to make the tech work. Google, however, is partnering with Fervo to tackle =
these challenges. The startup employees two technologies/strategies that gi=
ve it an advantage:=20
Fiber optic cables: gathering and analyze real-time data on flow, temperatu=
re, and performance of the resource, providing  insights into subsurface be=
havior at a resolution never before possible.
Precision horizontal drilling: precision directional drilling horizontally =
in geothermal reservoirs enables Fervo to drill multiple wells from a singl=
e location, lowering the surface footprint and reducing drilling risks. Hor=
izontal drilling also facilitates greater access to geologies that were pre=
viously challenging to reach, increasing the total resource potential for g=
eothermal energy.
In addition, partnering with Google gives them both the balance sheet to bu=
ild high upfront cost drilling locations and a built-in customer whose ener=
gy needs are only going to grow overtime. Whether it=E2=80=99s Microsoft pa=
rtnering with nuclear startups or Google partnering with Fervo, its clear t=
hat the leading technology companies of today will be major energy players =
in the future.=20
(5) AI is easy to control [ https://substack.com/redirect/8632797f-86d5-402=
8-b99d-c78b22759212?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Nora Belrose and Quintin Pope for AI Optimism
In what follows, we will argue that AI, even superhuman AI, will remain muc=
h more controllable than humans for the foreseeable future. Since each gene=
ration of controllable AIs can help control the next generation, it looks l=
ike this process can continue indefinitely, even to very high levels of cap=
ability.
We=E2=80=99re simple people. If you launch a movement with =E2=80=9Coptimis=
m=E2=80=9D in the name, and write thoughtful content about your optimism, y=
ou=E2=80=99re probably going to show up in the Weekly Dose of Optimism.=20
In this post, two ML researchers, Nora Belrose and Quintin Pope, make the c=
ase that AI is actually going to be way easier to control than humans are, =
even as it gets really smart.=20
=E2=80=9CThe =E2=80=98white box=E2=80=99 nature of AIs,=E2=80=9D they argue=
, =E2=80=9Cin contrast to the =E2=80=98black box=E2=80=99 of human cognitio=
n, enables precise and effective optimization and control methods that are =
impossible to use on organic brains.=E2=80=9D=20
What we like about the piece is that it doesn=E2=80=99t assume that there w=
on=E2=80=99t be any challenges with AI, or that it will magically be aligne=
d out of the box, but that people will continue to build tools to align the=
m. It=E2=80=99s a challenge, but optimism is realizing that challenges can =
be solved.=20
And it=E2=80=99s another example of the AI Narrative Tug-of-War [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/dacddab2-06b3-42fa-85a9-3e84976f5edf?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] making room in the midd=
le for nuanced and thoughtful narratives. If it=E2=80=99s closer to the e/a=
cc side, well=E2=80=A6 that=E2=80=99s because the e/acc side is more right.=
 We side with anyone who believes in humans=E2=80=99 ability to make the fu=
ture better, even if it takes some hard, smart work.
Bonus: Age of Miracles Episode 7
Listen on Spotify [ https://substack.com/redirect/a0139e07-aec1-4ab2-b76a-6=
bbfbd1abbda?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] or Apple [ https://substack.com/redirect/2f08bae0-8adb-4276-beaf-a37e=
5551b383?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ]
Packy here. Talk about perfect timing, we talk about Fervo in our latest ep=
isode of Age of Miracles and they show up in the news this week. Fervo isn=
=E2=80=99t a nuclear company, but this isn=E2=80=99t a nuclear episode.=20
Coming from outside the energy world, one of the things that struck me is h=
ow tribal energy is, as Nadia Asparouhova discusses in Mapping out the trib=
es of climate [ https://substack.com/redirect/f961f690-7351-4957-afd5-60969=
94fdf4d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
]. If you like solar, you have to hate nuclear. If you like nuclear, you ha=
ve to hate wind. If you like clean energy at all, you have to hate fossil f=
uels. Or whatever. That=E2=80=99s a generalization, of course, but it=E2=80=
=99s more true than it should be.=20
So even though this is a season on nuclear fission and fusion energy, the g=
oal isn=E2=80=99t the proliferation of any one energy source over another. =
It=E2=80=99s more energy and human flourishing, wherever it comes from.=20
For this episode, we talked to some of the smartest people we could find to=
 tell us why we=E2=80=99re wrong about nuclear, and why their energy source=
 of choice is the real answer. We talked to Casey Handmer and Noah Smith ab=
out solar, Angelica Oung about wind, Eli Dourado about geothermal (includin=
g Fervo), solar, wind, and batteries, and Alex Epstein and Mark Hinaman abo=
ut fossil fuels. Yup, fossil fuels. We also talked to Meredith Angwin, the =
Grandma of the Grid, about the electric grid that all of these sources feed=
 into.=20
I=E2=80=99m not a maximalist about anything except human progress and build=
ing an Age of Miracles. Check out the episode to see all of the ways we=E2=
=80=99ll power the growing demand for energy by the year 2050 =E2=80=94 our=
 amazing producer Nancy Xu [ https://substack.com/redirect/d04e6d8d-0331-4c=
07-9421-3dba40c51a32?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ] said it was her favorite yet!
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. If you have some time this weekend, check=
 out Percent=E2=80=99s private credit investing platform [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/1e4bdafa-d658-40f6-b54=
3-4a3d86d5cfe7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=20
We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tuesday.
Thanks for reading,
Dan + Packy

